## Instructions
---

You can integrate Google authentication with Cloudflare Access without a Google Workspace account. The integration will allow any user with a Google account to login (if the Access policy allows them to reach the resource). Unlike the instructions for [Google Workspace](/authentication/configuring-identity-providers/gsuite), the steps below will not allow you to pull group membership information from a Google Workspace account.

1. Visit the Google Cloud Platform console. Create a new project.

![Create Project](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/create-project.png)

2. Name the project and click **Create**.

![Name Project](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/name-project.png)

3. On the project home page that loads, select \`APIs & Services\` from the sidebar and click **Dashboard**.

![Name Project](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/click-api-dash.png)

4. You will first need to configure a consent screen. Click **Configure Consent Screen** at the top of the page.

![Click Consent](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/click-configure-consent.png)

5. Choose \`External\` as the User Type. Since this application is not being created in a Google Workspace account, the only types of users are external.

![Choose External](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/choose-external.png)

6. Name the application and add a support email (GCP will require you to add an email in your account).

![Name App](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/name-app.png)

You will also be prompted to input contact fields.

![Contact Fields](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/contact-fields.png)

7. In the \`Scopes\` section, we recommend adding the \`userinfo.email\` scope. This is not required for the integration to work, but will indicate to users authenticating what information is being gathered.

![Scopes](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/scopes.png)

You do not need to add test users.

![Test Users](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/test-users.png)

You can review the summary information and return to the dashboard at the bottom of the page.

![Summary](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/consent-screen-summary.png)

8. Return to the \`APIs & Services\` page and click **+ Create Credentials**. Select \`OAuth client ID\`.

![Create OAuth](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/create-oauth.png)

9. Name the application.

![Name OAuth](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/name-oauth.png)

10. You will need to input your Cloudflare authentication domain. The domain will be structured in the following format:

\`\`\`
https://<your-auth-domain-here>.cloudflareaccess.com
\`\`\`

Input the authentication domain without any path in the \`Authorized JavaScript origins\` section. In the Authorized redirect URIs section, input your authentication domain with the path below.

\`\`\`
https://<your-auth-domain-here>.cloudflareaccess.com/cdn-cgi/access/callback
\`\`\`

![Auth Domain](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/auth-domain.png)

11. Google will present the OAuth Client ID and Secret values. The secret field functions like a password and should be kept securely and not shared. For the purposes of this tutorial, the secret field is kept visible. Copy both values.

![Secret Field](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/oauth-created.png)

16. Navigate to the Cloudflare for Teams dashboard. In the \`Authentication\` page of the Access section, click **+ Add**.

![Add IdP](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/add-idp.png)

17. Select \`Google\`.

![Add Google](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/add-google.png)

18. Input the Client ID and Client Secret fields generated previously. Click **Save**.

![Add Google Suite](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/input-client.png)

21. You can now return to the list of identity providers in the \`Authentication\` page of the Cloudflare for Teams dashboard. Select Google Suite and click **Test**.

Your user identity should return.

![Connection Works](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/google/connection-works.png)

## Instructions
---

You can integrate Microsoft Azure AD\xAE (Active Directory) with Cloudflare for Teams and build rules based on user identity and group membership. Users will authenticate with their Azure AD credentials and login to resources protected by Cloudflare Access or enroll into Cloudflare Gateway.

1. Sign in to [the Azure dashboard](https://portal.azure.com/).

![Azure AD Portal](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/azure-portal.png)

2. Click **Azure Active Directory** in the Azure Services section.

![Azure AD Select AD](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/pick-azure-ad.png)

3. On the **Azure AD** dashboard, click **App registrations** in the **Manage** section of the _Azure Active Directory_ pane.

![Azure AD App Registration](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/click-app-reg.png)

4. Click **+ New registration**.

![Azure AD New Registration](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/click-new-reg.png)

5. Name your application and enter your **Cloudflare Authentication Domain**. The format of the authentication domain will be \`https://<your authentication domain>/cdn-cgi/access/callback\`). Click **Register**.

![Azure AD Cloudflare Access App](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/name-app.png)

6. On the following screen, copy the \`Application (client) ID\` and \`Directory (tenant ID\`. You will need to input these values into the Cloudflare dashboard.

![Azure AD IDs](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/client-directory-ids.png)

7. In the left hand panel, click **Certificates & Secrets** to create an Application Secret.

![Azure AD Certs and Secrets](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/certs-and-secrets.png)

8. Click **+ New client secret**. Name the client secret and choose an expiration. Click **Add**.

![Azure AD Certs and Secrets](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/name-client-cert.png)

Copy the \`Value\` field of the client secret. Treat this value like a password. This example leaves the value visible so the values in Azure can be seen in the Access configuration.

![Azure AD Certs and Secrets](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/client-cert-value.png)

9. In the left hand panel, select **API permissions**. Click **Add a permission**.

![Azure AD API Permissions](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/api-perms.png)

10. Click **Microsoft Graph**.

![Azure AD API Permissions](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/microsoft-graph.png)

11. Select Delegated permissions. You will need to toggle 7 specific permissions in the next page. Once toggled, click **Add permissions**.

    - email
    - openid
    - profile
    - offline_access
    - User.Read
    - Directory.Read.All
    - Group.Read.All

![Azure AD API Permissions](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/request-perms.png)

12. On the next page, click the button that begins **Grant Admin Consent for ...**.

![Azure AD API Permissions](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/configured-perms.png)

13. Return to the Cloudflare for Teams dashboard. Select \`Authentication\` under the Access section of the sidebar. In the \`Login\` tab, click **+ Add**. Choose \`Azure AD\` on the next page.

![Azure AD Add Identity](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/add-identity.png)

14. Input the \`Application ID\`, \`Application secret\`, and \`Directory ID\` values from Azure.

If you are using Azure AD groups, toggle **Support Groups** slider **On** in the **Edit your Azure AD identity provider** window.

![Azure AD Add Identity](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/add-azure-ad.png)

15. Click **Save and Test** to check your connection to the IdP.

![Azure AD Test](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/valid-test.png)

## Using AzureAD Groups

AzureAD exposes directory groups in a format that consists of random strings, the \`Object Id\`, that is distinct from the \`Name\`. In the example below, the group named "Admins" has an ID of "61503835-b6fe-4630-af88-de551dd59a2".

![Azure AD Test Connection](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/object-id.png)

When configuring Access to use Azure groups, you must input the \`Object Id\`.

![Azure AD Test Connection](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/azure/group-config.png)

**Note: You must be an admin for the GSuite organization to connect your account.**


You can integrate a Google Workspace (formerly Google Suite) account with Cloudflare Access. Unlike the instructions for [generic Google authentication](/authentication/configuring-identity-providers/google), the steps below will allow you to pull group membership information from your Google Workspace account.

Once integrated, users will login with their Google Suite credentials to reach resources protected by Cloudflare Access or to enroll their device into Cloudflare Gateway.

1. Log in the Google Cloud Platform [console][https://console.cloud.google.com/]. This is separate from your Google Workspace console.

![GCP Console](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/gcp-home.png)

2. Click **Create Project** to create a new project. Name the project and click **Create**.

![Create Project](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/create-project.png)

You should now see a Dashboard for your project.

![Post Create](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/post-create.png)

3. On the left-hand side, select \`APIs & Services\` and click **Dashboard**.

![Click API](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/click-api.png)

4. In the screen that loads, click **+ Enable APIs and Services** in the top toolbar.

![Enable API](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/enable-api.png)

5. The API Library will load. Search for \`admin\` in the search bar.

![API Library](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/api-library.png)

6. Select \`Admin SDK API\` by Google.

![Admin SDK](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/admin-sdk.png)

7. Click **Enable** on the Admin SDK API page.

![Admin SDK](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/enable-admin-sdk.png)

The Admin SDK will be added to your project.

![Admin SDK](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/post-enable.png)

8. Return to the APIs & Services page. Click **Credentials** in the navigation bar. You will see a warning that you need to configure a consent screen. Click **Configure Consent Screen**.

![Configure Consent Screen](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/configure-consent-screen.png)

9. Cloudflare Access will gather information about users in your Google Workspace account, but not other accounts. Toggle \`Internal\` to limit this to members in your account.

![Internal Users](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/consent-internal.png)

10. Input information about the application.

![App Domain](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/consent-screen-app-name.png)

In this case, you are making an application available to your users and can add your team's contact information.

![Internal Users](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/consent-screen-contact.png)

You will not need to configure scopes in this screen and can leave these fields blank.

![Consent Screen Scope](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/consent-screen-scope.png)

The summary page will load and you can save and exit.

![Consent Screen Summary](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/consent-screen-summary.png)

11. Return to the \`Credentials\` page. Click **+ Create Credentials**

![Create Credentials](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/create-credentials.png)

12. Select **OAuth client ID**.

![Select OAuth](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/select-oauth.png)

13. Select \`Web application\` as the Application type.

![Create OAuth](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/create-oauth.png)

14. You will need to input your Cloudflare authentication domain. The domain will be structured in the following format:

\`\`\`
https://<your-auth-domain-here>.cloudflareaccess.com
\`\`\`

Input the authentication domain without any path in the \`Authorized JavaScript origins\` section. In the Authorized redirect URIs section, input your authentication domain with the path below.

\`\`\`
https://<your-auth-domain-here>.cloudflareaccess.com/cdn-cgi/access/callback
\`\`\`

![Input Auth Domain](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/input-auth-domain.png)

Click **Create**.

15. Google will present the OAuth Client ID and Secret values. The secret field functions like a password and should be kept securely and not shared. For the purposes of this tutorial, the secret field is kept visible. Copy both values.

![Secret Field](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/secret-field.png)

The Client ID will now appear in the \`APIs & Services\` page.

![Client ID Visible](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/client-id-visible.png)

16. Navigate to the Cloudflare for Teams dashboard. In the \`Authentication\` page of the Access section, click **+ Add**.

![Add IdP](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/add-idp.png)

17. Select \`Google Suite\`.

![Add Google Suite](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/add-gsuite.png)

18. Input the Client ID and Client Secret fields generated previously. Additionally, input the domain of your Google Workspace account. Click **Save**.

![Add Google Suite](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/input-client.png)

19. To complete setup, you must scroll below and visit the link generated. If you are not the Google Workspace administrator, share the link with the administrator.

![Visit Link](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/visit-link.png)

20. The generated link will prompt you to login to your Google account and to authorize Cloudflare Access to view group information.

![Authorize Groups](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/authorize-groups.png)

A success page will then load from Cloudflare Access.

![Group Success](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/group-success.png)

21. You can now return to the list of identity providers in the \`Authentication\` page of the Cloudflare for Teams dashboard. Select Google Suite and click **Test**.

Your user identity and group membership should return.

![Connection Works](https://dev-docs.cloudflareaccess.org/access/static/gsuite/connection-works.png)
